Besides the proper articles, the treatise contains two addenda—“On the Guarantee of Perpetual Peace” and a “secret article”—of which the first is particularly noteworthy, for it contains the philosophical justification of the entire project. There Kant develops his key idea of the philosophy of history (already presented in the #emph[Idei powszechniej historii…];) of nature as a naturalized providence#footnote[As Siemek notes, this substitution of nature for proper history is a heritage of the Enlightenment philosophy—“Kant’s ‘nature’ (‘przyroda’) is here a cryptonym of the very #emph[historicity] of human socialization” (M.J. Siemek, #emph[Filozofia wobec wyzwań społecznej modernizacji];, in: #emph[HF] p. 165).];, realizing in history its ultimate end—the “moralization” of the human. War is inscribed into this naturalist‑teleological narrative, the Kantian historiosophy, becoming responsible for driving people into the farthest corners of the earth and for establishing the original legal relations between them#footnote[See #emph[Do wiecznego pokoju];, op. cit., p. 183.];. However, in the modern era, in which the bourgeois spirit of commerce reigns and the feudal warrior has been replaced by the bourgeois upstart, war ought to be displaced by peace.

Just as nature, on the one hand, wisely separated nations, among which the will of each state—even one grounded in international law itself—would gladly like, by cunning or force, to subordinate other states, so, on the other hand, it unites, by the power of mutual, advantageous interest, those nations which the concept of cosmopolitan right would not protect from violence and war. This is the #emph[spirit of commerce];, which cannot coexist with war and will sooner or later take hold of every nation. Since, of all the powers (means) subordinate to state authority, the #emph[power of money] proves the most reliable, states feel compelled (naturally not by moral motives) to support an honest peace and, wherever war would threaten in the world, to prevent it through their mediation, as if they were in a lasting alliance for this purpose; for great alliances formed for war can, by their nature, very rarely be realized, and even more rarely be successful. In this way, through the very mechanism of human inclinations, nature guarantees perpetual peace (…)#footnote[Ibid., p. 187.];.
]

In the foregoing argument, Kant maintained that it is nature which, through the universal civil republic established by humans, carries the promise of perpetual peace. Yet in the passage above one can discern the hidden material condition of Kant’s project of peace: “the #emph[power of money] proves the most reliable.” Thus it is the #emph[rule of capitalist social relations];, the global market, that turns out to be the foundation of the #emph[rule of law and morality] in the cosmopolitan aspect. The very idea of cosmopolitanism is therefore a cryptonym of world capital—the more trade, the more international circulation of goods and money, the closer to universal peace. Kant again appears as a leading ideologue of the bourgeois-capitalist public sphere. It is not the finite human and the always limited deeds of the individual, nor even nature, the ruse steering history, but precisely money that possesses the real power to establish peace: “What I am not able to do as a #emph[human];, what all the forces of my individual being are not able to do, I am able to do with the help of #emph[money];”#footnote[K. Marx, #emph[Rękopisy ekonomiczno--filozoficzne z 1844 r.];, in: K. Marks, F. Engels, #emph[Dzieła];, vol. 1, op. cit., p. 612.];.
